lings rather than facts, familiar recurring tropes of heroism, terrorism, entrepreneurship, and canine love make the war easier to comprehend and elicit sympathy for US military forces. An indictment of US policy, Bose demonstrates that contemporary imperialism operates on an ideologically diverse cultural terrain to enlist support for the war across the political spectrum.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAfghan War, 2001-xLiterature and the war. 0aAfghan War, 2001-xMass media and the war. 0aAfghan War, 2001-. 0aImperialism. 0aIntervention (International law). 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAfghanistan, United States, War on terror, terrorism, cultural representations, US intervention, foreign policy, imperial foreign policy, imperialism, contemporary imperialism, Orientalist stereotypes, Cold War, 911, heroism, entrepreneurship, canine love, US military forces, ideologically diverse cultural terrain.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831106903300 cprintz978197880599640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978806023?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978806023423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978806023/original  a978-3-11-069033-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  